To give me some comfort and as an eye opening...
Note: this is in a 12 month period!

https://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/estimates_2009_h1n1.htm

CDC Estimates of 2009 H1N1 Influenza Cases, Hospitalizations and Deaths in the United States
During the pandemic, CDC provided estimates of the numbers of 2009 H1N1 cases, hospitalizations and deaths on seven different occasions.
Final estimates were published in 2011.
These final estimates were that from April 12, 2009 to April 10, 2010 approximately....
60.8 million cases (range: 43.3-89.3 million),
274,304 hospitalizations (195,086-402,719), and
12,469 deaths (8868-18,306) occurred in the United States due to pH1N1.
These final estimates are available at: Estimating the burden of 2009 pandemic influenza A (H1N1) in the United States (April 2009-April 2010)External Web Site Icon, Shrestha SS, et al., Clin Infect Dis. 2011 Jan 1;52 Suppl 1:S75-82.

snippet.textDisplay: I was in China when the outbreak occurred. When I came back to the States on Feb 6th, I was truly surprised and disappointed about how disorganized and ill-equipped CDC was. When we landed in LAX, the staff from CDC were waiting at the gate with a thermometer. Before letting me go, she did say that someone would check on me. Up till now- March 3rd, no one from CDC has reached out. I tried my best to isolate myself within the following two weeks, but if I had wanted to go out and connect with people, there wouldn't have been no one to stop me. The U.S. government just hasn't taken this seriously. Meanwhile, they continue letting people from Japan, Korea, and Italy to come in.We will see cases, a lot more.

snippet.textDisplay:
Which virus makes you sicker?

As of Feb. 22, in the current season there were at least 32 million cases of flu in the United States, 310,000 hospitalizations and 18,000 flu deaths, according to the C.D.C. Hospitalization rates among children and young adults this year have been unusually high.

There would be even more illnesses and deaths if there were no flu vaccine. Most people recover in less than two weeks, and sometimes in just days.

By contrast, about 70 people in the United States have been infected with the new coronavirus, and there has been one death. There are no treatments or vaccines for the coronavirus, only supportive care for infected people.

From nytimes. Com
